    <title>Combined summary - [BIP Draft] Segregated Data: a prunable, script-isolated block region for data carriage</title>
    <updated>2026-07-02T05:02:39.936184+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://delvingbitcoin.org/t/bip-draft-segregated-data-a-prunable-script-isolated-block-region-for-data-carriage/2641/35" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2026-06-23 16:40:23.660000+00:00</published>
    <summary>The proposed Segregated Data (SegData) framework aims to optimize data handling within Bitcoin blocks by introducing a method that segregates certain types of data from transactional data. This new structure allows for efficient storage and management of non-transactional data, minimizing its impact on node resources during processes such as Initial Block Download (IBD) and regular operations. SegData leverages a distinct Merkle root for in-block commitments and enables optional pruning post-validation, which can be particularly advantageous for nodes not requiring long-term retention of this data.
Key features of SegData include its alignment with the BIP-141 structure, incorporating a coinbase output for commitment over a separate Merkle root, modifications to block serialization, and an extension of the weight formula. Furthermore, it introduces reference outputs that are witness v2, hold no value, are unspendable, and are excluded from the UTXO set, ensuring prunability and non-transaction triggering. The depth-scoped validation allows for full enforcement within a standard retention window and reduced checks thereafter, optimizing synchronization across nodes.
Potential adopters of SegData could include off-chain data interpreters like indexers for application-layer assets, timestamping services, and attestations. However, data requiring script evaluations at spend time cannot migrate to this system due to the isolation of scripts from entry contents. The implementation specifics of SegData still have open questions concerning the management of witness slots and transaction weight calculations, as well as the balance between aiding node pairing for data retrieval and protecting privacy against fingerprinting threats.
There are discussions about the resource implications of full nodes processing data at the tip, specifically the CPU cycles required for validating each block's hash. While this is a resource-intensive process, the design of SegData does not increase network or storage costs since it involves moving data rather than adding new data. Nodes have the option to opt out of storing SegData, potentially reducing their bandwidth, CPU, and storage resource needs. This strategic approach to resource management highlights how SegData could offer a more flexible and efficient solution compared to existing data storage methods within blockchain networks.
In summary, SegData presents a structured, cost-effective approach to managing data within the Bitcoin blockchain, helping to differentiate between data handling and monetary transactions while maintaining the overall functionality and efficiency of the system. It proposes a more modernized and optimized framework that addresses both the technical and operational needs of the blockchain community, potentially leading to significant improvements in how data is managed across the network. These developments reflect an ongoing dialogue aimed at refining the proposal to ensure clarity and effectiveness in practical applications.</summary>
